Lesson 4: Malware—What It Is and How to Defend Against It

Summary:
Malware (short for malicious software) is any program designed to harm your computer, steal data, or cause damage. It includes viruses, worms, ransomware, spyware, and more. In this lesson, you’ll learn how malware works, how it spreads, and how to protect yourself.

Key Concepts:

    Types of Malware:

        Virus: Attaches to files and spreads when the file is opened.

        Worm: Spreads on its own without needing a file.

        Ransomware: Locks your files and demands payment to unlock them.

        Spyware: Secretly monitors your activity and steals data.

        Trojan: Disguises itself as legitimate software but has a hidden malicious purpose.

    How Malware Spreads:

        Email Attachments: Opening infected files.

        Downloads: Installing software from untrusted sources.

        USB Drives: Plugging in infected devices.

        Malicious Websites: Visiting unsafe sites or clicking on ads.

    Signs of Infection:

        Slow computer performance.

        Pop-ups or strange messages.

        Files disappearing or being locked.

        Unusual network activity.

    Defending Against Malware:

        Use antivirus software and keep it updated.

        Avoid clicking on suspicious links or downloading unknown files.

        Keep your operating system and software up to date with patches.

        Regularly back up your data to recover from attacks.

Exercises:

    Malware Research:

        Pick one type of malware (e.g., ransomware, spyware). Research a real-world example (e.g., WannaCry, Pegasus). Write a short summary of how it worked and the damage it caused.

    Antivirus Setup:

        Download and install a free antivirus program (e.g., Windows Defender, Avast). Run a full scan on your computer. Write down what it found (if anything) and how it works.

    Spot the Malware:

        Imagine you receive an email with the subject “Your Invoice is Ready!” and an attachment called “invoice.exe.” Write a paragraph explaining why this might be malware and what you should do.

    Backup Practice:

        Back up your important files to an external drive or cloud storage (e.g., Google Drive, OneDrive). Write down the steps you took and why backups are important.

    Malware Prevention Plan:

        Create a list of 5 rules to follow to avoid malware (e.g., “Don’t open email attachments from strangers”). Share it with a friend or family member.

    Simulated Attack:

        Use a safe, simulated malware tool (e.g., EICAR Test File [https://www.eicar.org/download-anti-malware-testfile/] ) to test your antivirus. Write down what happened and how your antivirus responded.

By the end of this lesson, you’ll understand how malware works, how to spot it, and how to protect yourself. In the next lesson, we’ll dive into networks and how to secure them.

