Lesson 5: Networks and Network Security

Summary:
A network is a group of connected devices (like computers, phones, and printers) that can share data. Networks are everywhere—your home Wi-Fi, your school’s computers, and even the internet itself. But networks can also be a target for attackers. In this lesson, you’ll learn how networks work, what makes them vulnerable, and how to secure them.

Key Concepts:

    How Networks Work:

        Devices communicate using protocols (rules) like HTTP (for websites) and IP (for sending data).

        Data is broken into packets and sent across the network.

        Networks can be wired (using cables) or wireless (using Wi-Fi).

    Network Vulnerabilities:

        Weak Passwords: Easy-to-guess Wi-Fi passwords.

        Unencrypted Data: Data sent without encryption can be intercepted.

        Open Ports: Unused network services that attackers can exploit.

        Rogue Devices: Unauthorized devices connected to the network.

    Network Security Tools:

        Firewalls: Block unauthorized access to the network.

        Encryption: Scrambles data so only authorized users can read it (e.g., WPA3 for Wi-Fi).

        Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS): Monitor for suspicious activity.

        Virtual Private Networks (VPNs): Encrypt your internet traffic to protect privacy.

    Securing a Network:

        Use strong passwords for Wi-Fi and routers.

        Enable encryption (e.g., WPA3) on your Wi-Fi.

        Keep router firmware updated.

        Disable unused network services.

Exercises:

    Network Map:

        Draw a map of your home or school network. Include all devices (e.g., computers, phones, smart TVs) and how they’re connected (e.g., Wi-Fi, Ethernet).

    Wi-Fi Security Check:

        Log in to your Wi-Fi router’s settings (check the manual for instructions). Check if it’s using WPA3 or WPA2 encryption. If not, write down how to enable it.

    Firewall Test:

        Use a free online tool like ShieldsUP! to test your network’s firewall. Write down the results and what they mean.

    VPN Experiment:

        Download a free VPN (e.g., ProtonVPN, Windscribe). Connect to a server and visit a website like WhatIsMyIPAddress.com. Write down how your IP address changed and why VPNs are useful.

    Rogue Device Hunt:

        Check your Wi-Fi router’s connected devices list. Identify all devices and make sure they belong to you. If you find an unknown device, write down how you’d investigate it.

    Network Security Plan:

        Imagine you’re setting up a network for a small business. Write a list of 5 steps to secure it (e.g., “Enable WPA3 encryption,” “Install a firewall”).

By the end of this lesson, you’ll understand how networks work, what makes them vulnerable, and how to protect them. In the next lesson, we’ll explore social engineering—how attackers trick people into giving up sensitive information.

